com.apriori.apt.reflect

Class ArWildcardType

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.apriori.apt.reflect.ArWildcardType
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ArType

    public class ArWildcardType
extends Object
implements ArType
    A wildcard type. Wildcards indicates unknown (but optionally bounded) values for type parameters. This is analogous to WildcardType, except that it represents types in Java source (during annotation processing) vs. representing runtime types.
    See Also:
    WildcardType

      • getExtendsBound

        public ArType getExtendsBound()
        Returns a bound that the wildcard type must extend. This will be the type referenced in an optional extends clause on the wildcard. For example, in the type List<? extends Number>, the type parameter is a wildcard type with a bound of Number. If no explicit bound exists for the wildcard then java.lang.Object is the implied bound.

        This method varies from the analogous method in java.lang.reflect.WildcardType since that method's return value implies that wildcard types can have multiple bounds. As of Java 7, wildcard types can only have a single upper bound. (though ArTypeVariables can have more than one). Also the word extends is used in the name as it is more explicit than the word upper (which is arguably confusing).

        Returns:
        the wildcard's upper bound
        See Also:
        WildcardType.getUpperBounds(), WildcardType.getExtendsBound()

      • getSuperBound

        public ArType getSuperBound()
        Returns a bound of which the wildcard type must be a super-type. This will be the type referenced in an optional super clause on the wildcard. For example, in the type List<? super Integer>, the type parameter is a wildcard type with a bound of Integer.

        This method varies from the analogous method in java.lang.reflect.WildcardType since that method's return value implies that wildcard types can have multiple bounds. As of Java 7, wildcard types can only have at most one lower bound. Also the word super is used in the name as it is more explicit than the word lower (which is arguably confusing).

        Returns:
        the wildcard's lower bound or null if it has no lower bound
        See Also:
        WildcardType.getLowerBounds(), WildcardType.getSuperBound()

      • toTypeString

        public String toTypeString()
        Description copied from interface: ArType
        Returns a string representation of this type, suitable for constructing a representation of this type that could be used in Java source code. For most types, this is the same as toString(), but one glaring exception to that is in ArClass where toString() and toGenericString() return representations that resemble type declarations but toTypeString() returns a string that is a simple reference to the class's raw/erased type.
        Specified by:
        toTypeString in interface ArType
        Returns:
        a string representation of this type
